On my way to making an adjustable jack stand (I'm still working on that) I made a neat little fidget toy that my kids love fiddling with so I'm sharing it with the community

Printer:

Maker Select i3 and PowerSpec Ultra

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20

Infill:

20%

Notes:

~3 shells is recommended.

Print instructions:

  1. Print as oriented - You'll get both parts in one print. There is a 1mm gap between parts so they should not fuse unless you have extreme elephant foot.
  2. After print, remove from bed and carefully use a thin blade to slice any joins on the bottom layer. (don't completely remove the elephant foot - it's important in step 4).
  3. Pressing down (towards the little protruding feet) will help separate the part.
  4. After loosening the ring from the center part, completely twist it off and put it on upside down. With the ring upside down, the little bit of elephant foot on each part will create a nice barrier to prevent the parts from coming apart with gentle force.

*I have added a taller version (taller inner part) with same 25mm ring. I'll also add a taller version with a taller 75mm ring later.

Can Man is a man made from a can.

Plant grass seed in my head to make my hair. Print the eyes and mouth to give me a face.

Notes:

These need to be printed with fairly dense support structure. A raft is a good idea to give a good base for the support material.

I used ABS, but PLA will be fine too.
Remix from AdamPyschny mount. I shortened the connectors a bit and made a slight angle so they snap in easier. Also they are made for Turnigy 2S 300 mAh batteries.

While doubting if I wanted a magnetic implant so I could feel electronics. I made a ring to test the feel out. It works great! I used flexible filament because I thought it would be a snug fit, but it wasn't needed because it turns out I have on idea how to measure fingers properly.

I used a magnet i had lying around with a diameter of 12mm and a height of 4mm. The magnet can also be thinner, but I couldn't squeak more millimeters in the holder without the ring becoming too bulky.

For mounting the magnet, I used some hot glue. PLA is possible, but there is a chance that the ring will partly melted by the hot glue.

description.text:
With two of these tablets/phones up to at least 7" can be set to lean at an 67, 44, 27 or 13 degree (approximate) angle on top of this, but limited to landscape orientation. A 10mm thick tablet might not fit (maybe if you file some out of the openings), but anything below that should work.
For portrait orientation you need another pair; two connected ones elongates the horizontal surface.

Two of them can be "folded" in the sense that they can be joined if you reverse one.
70 by 34mm, 10+10mm thick - a folded pair can be kept in a trouser pocket.

Limited testing on this version, the 6 previous versions has been in use for some time.

Printer:

FFCP 2016

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Tested with 0.15mm, 0.4mm nozzle

5%

Notes:

Calibrate your printer!
Without calibration you will most likely need to file/sand on the mating pins and holes. Even so with a calibration that doesn't allow clearance.

Dual head printer? 34mm or more between heads: Then you can ditto-print two of these at a time.

110 degree TRUE bed temperature with ABS prints (use an IR thermometer!) to avoid most of the warping.
I use a glass bed with a thin layer of ABS/Acetone slurry, it lets go of the print when it cools down below 65 degrees C.

Designed in FreeCAD on Ubuntu Linux

description.text: This is a 1.5" dust collection hose riser for the MPCNC. The riser keeps the vacuum hose and cabling to the router out of the way and off the stepper belts. Cabling can quickly be adjusted/changed via the snap close wiring mounts.

For my MPCNC build, I am using 1.5" vacuum hose (actually 1.5" bulge pump hose from Home Depot) connected to a shopvac for my dust collection system. To keep the hose for hitting the belts and just getting in the way of the x-axis on my MPCNC build, I made a hose riser to keep the dust collection hose vertical and out of the way of the MPCNC during cutting.

The riser uses (2) two 3D printed lower mounts that are screwed into the back of the MPCNC table, (1) one 3D printed upper mount. The mounts are designed to tightly slide onto standard 3/4" aluminum angle from Home Depot. The hose is then zip tied around the aluminum angle.

As an added bonus, I included an all 3D printed hinge/clasp that holds all of the wiring that needs to run out to the router and gantry (z-axis motor lines, router power cable, z-axis end stops, or whatever else you desire). That's right - nothing to assembly. Just print the mounts slide in the aluminum angle, screw to your MPCNC table and then just clip the cables in and zip tie the hose to the riser.

For the business end of this dust collection system, I am using a modified Das Boot design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1875449) and a homemade dust skirt that I made from duct and electrical tape. My system is powered by a cheap $20 Buckethead vac from Home Depot that fit over a standard 5 gallon bucket. So, all in I spent about $35 on this dust collection system for my MPCNC.

Parts for the riser:

• (2) 3D printed bottom mounts

• (1) 3D printed top mount

• 3/4 in. x 36 in. Aluminum Angle Bar (1/16 in thickness)
http://www.homedepot.com/p/Everbilt-3-4-in-x-36-in-Aluminum-Angle-Bar-with-1-16-in-Thick-801377/204273984

• #8 1/2 in. Phillips Pan-Head Sheet Metal Screws (100-Pack)
http://www.homedepot.com/p/Crown-Bolt-8-1-2-in-Phillips-Pan-Head-Sheet-Metal-Screws-100-Pack-24762/100349331

• 8 in. UV Cable Tie - Black (100-Pack)
http://www.homedepot.com/p/Commercial-Electric-8-in-UV-Cable-Tie-Black-100-Pack-GT-200STCB/203531910

Dust collection parts (Optional):

• 1 1/2 in. Discharge Hose Kit
http://www.homedepot.com/p/1-1-2-in-Discharge-Hose-Kit-66000-WYN1/100119536?MERCH=REC-_-SearchPLPHorizontal1_rr-_-NA-_-100119536-_-N

• 5 gal. 1.75-Peak HP Wet Dry Vac
http://www.homedepot.com/p/Bucket-Head-5-gal-1-75-Peak-HP-Wet-Dry-Vac-BH0100/202017218

STEP 1

Print (2) two 3D printed lower mounts and (1) one 3D printed upper mount. I used 20% infill and printed in black ABS.

STEP 2

Slide the (2) two bottom mounts onto the 3/4" aluminum angle. The position will depend on your MPCNC table design, but try to space them far enough apart to get a stable mounting.

Now, slide the upper mount onto the opposite end of the aluminum angle.

STEP 3

Snap your 1.5" dust collection hose into the 3D printed mounts. Then secure the hose with zip ties.

STEP 4

Run your cables through cable holder and snap the clasp closed. If you want to make your build cleaner, zip tie the cables to the dust collection hose out to the router/gantry.

title: Blower Attachment Bracket for the Back

description.text:
After installing the Titan Aero, I wanted to move the blower to the back of the carriage so it is easier to operate the Titan extruder. This is a simple plate that uses already existing threaded holes on the original Anet A8 motor/extruder bracket. Here I am using a Titan Aero carriage bracket made by MCSTAN ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2234921 ) which he also carried over those two existing attachments.

I first had the blower sideways but that didn't work because it was hitting the vertical acrylic walls. Then I turned it 90 degrees and after printing so it would sit in the middle of the mount plate, I saw it wasn't in line with the nozzle. So moved it to the outside of one of the mount legs. In my picture you can see where I still have half of the clipped leg. But the attached file, v3, has this leg already removed.

I also had to limit the maximum X travel so the fan would not hit the far acrylic wall, but the nozzle still covered the bed all the way.

Next is a nozzle for this setup...

Thanks for MCSTAN to do the harder part which was the carriage mount for the Titan Aero!!

FIRST UPDATE:
After printing and installing this duct ( https://www.thingiverse.com/make:335412 ) from MrBlom, I had to do some tweeks... The blower needed to sit further away from the carriage and higher. So here is v4!!

description.text:
I really like cruzher's drawer system, and the idea of wschadow's remix to expand to double drawers. But there are some limitation to me, so I decided to remix it.

Changes from the original design :

  • Shelves original design are based on tongues to receive the drawers, when you want a double drawer you need to print the shelf that correspond to it. I gone to the opposite way, shelves are made with grooves, avec drawers have a tongue, that let you to print a drawer of any height and place it anywhere into the shelf,

  • I wanted the shelves stackable horizontally and vertically for an easy scale up, this version let you attach shelves together with M4x10mm csk screws and M4 nuts, side to side or bottom to top

  • The shelves are wall mountable, each one have 4 5mm holes at the back

  • Shelves are available from 2 to 15 drawers high

  • Backward compatible with the orignal drawers, just print the small Original_Drawer_Adapter.stl and glue your drawer on it, it will fit to the new design

  • Each drawers are available from 1U to 6U

  • Little redesign of the handles, less round for easier print

Shelves are optimized to print with 0% infill, print faster with less material than the original design (not so much, just a little bit)

Feel free to ask any layout, I used a 12x12 grid, so ask any combination that fit into the grid.

You can find a parametric drawer (rows and columns) here, thanks to _WG_ : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2552468

1: Battery tray for shorty lipo. This uses the stock holes in the chassis. Use this for batteries that are 96 x 47mm. The fit is snug but not too tight.

2: Spring collars so you can use newer bigbore shock springs on the worlds car shocks. You'll also need Associated part 91310 12 mm Shock Spring Cups kit, which is very cheap.
This combo is very smooth and eliminates spring rub.

It was printed slowly, with a 0.2mm nozzle at 0.05 layer height. Check out the printing details below for more information.

Cleaned with an X-ACTO Knife, then sanded with 500 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust readings for a few voltage values (you can also view these in the images):

  • 1.5V => 15.23 grams
  • 2V => 21.42 grams
  • 2.5V => 27.04 grams
  • 3V => 41.98 grams

The included files contain all the pictures taken during the test, along with 6 txt files which contain the airfoil in various positions (rotated, scaled and translated on the Z axis), the STL files and the SLDPRT files. If you want to use this propeller, make sure you get a 8520 coreless motor.

If you were to reassemble them, insert them in SolidWorks as "Curves through XYZ" in ascending order. Then, through a few processes, you can get to the design of this propeller. You'll notice the Z value is incremented by 5mm each time. If you modify this value, you'll end up with either a longer or a shorter version of the propeller blade.

Use the two SLDPRT files, in case you want to make your own changes to the propeller.

Notes: Airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
Design submitted on Pinshape contest : Envision The Future Design Challenge
https://pinshape.com/items/35262-3d-printed-octa-b-bearing

Starting from the idea that alphabet is easier to memorize if student can create and touch characters by himself, i tried to find a way to compose Braille character easily even for visually impaired people with a tactile tool. Since all characters can be created using 2 series of 8 different combinations, i designed 2 octagon parts with all dot combination faces, linked by standard roller-type bearing to allow relative rotation between both parts.

After trying many configurations of dot repartitions (same way like how to dispose letter on keyboard), i assume that the more practical configuration is when a half turn gives the opposite result, meaning that, in example dot 1-3 becomes dot 2 when turning 180 degrees the part. That point could be confirmed or updated if better proposal, however, i suggest to have the part with the screw on your left hand side before starting, that could help you memorizing the relative location.

I hope that this concept could be used by visually impaired people and teachers, and why not every one interested by learning Braille. I'm playing with it, waiting in the cue or in the subway to spend time, searching at the fastest way to go through alphabet without seeing it, but only touching ... and as of now, i do understand all those weird dots in my elevator command panel :-) .

An another version with Standard size characters to create words and sentences with multiple characters is in progress ... if you are interested by more, just let me know ...

Let's print and enjoy !

description.text:
UPDATE!!!
I've uploaded the No Tendrils egg that includes a base. The base is necessary since it cuts through two layers of the model to create an internal support structure to build the lower bowl of the inside of the egg.
Who cares? WELL if you want a 0% infill egg that you can shine a light through and not see those infill line structures, then this is the way to go! I'm keeping the normal support at the bottom as well for extra support but it's printed without issue on 0% infill.
Printing fast with a low retraction will give strings on the inside which add some support internally too without the human/machine made looking lines.

Sorry for the odd size comparisons but the body of the tape is 2" so it's 7.5" total. I filled and coated the egg in ABS/Acetone so it should eventually (after another coat) be water and generally chemically resistant. The skin is nice and smooth too and it's still transparent with the 1mm shell :D
So next is to continue the fill and coating of ABS/Acetone and then some paint and latex. Then fill the tendrils, connect then, and I'm done!
One note about filling the egg. Drilling the points where the tendrils connect is not a good idea since the 1mm shell makes it too fragile. That didn't work out for the lower right corner in the pic with the green egg since I drilled that one. I did however use a small propane torch and an x-acto knife to cut out and/or move the PLA around for the rest so I had a large enough hole to fill the model with a funnel, without destroying the shell.
The yellow slime part is a really bad ABS brand from Shaxon that seems to be more PVC than ABS but the effect actually worked perfectly so the entire shell and innards is coated in liquid melted plastic :)

##################################################
DO NOT let the CAD view fool you. This thing is HUGE!!!
Full scale is 474mm X x 474mm Y x 175mm Z
or
18in X x 18in Y x 7in Z

Firstly AGISIS really is owed a lot of credit since he's the inspiration for everyone's design which this is remixed from AND he took some hard hits to make it happen. If you're looking at this you likely love Aliens and the Alien series. If not perhaps you will soon enjoy it too! AGISIS brought to life something that many of us had wished for and for the longest time had to spend 100s to 1000s of dollars to get a subpar model of something that sort of resembles what we saw in the movies. It's the creepiest prop ever! So now it has a home :)

I really liked AGISIS' face hugger and I've been needing an egg for it. Babelique was awesome enough to create one however the bottom just seemed like it needed more.
MustangDave made a great egg but it was closed and the overall model small. It's vector so of course you can scale it.
Either way I took all these ideas and models and meshed them together to build what I'd consider a more appropriate egg which includes the tendrils from MustangDave, the egg from Babelique, and then some sculpting on the lower portions of the egg to give it a more movie-like look.

If you want to make money off this model, WELL GO AHEAD! But do please pay tribute to all the artists involved. Otherwise enjoy and thank you!

What's uploaded here:
I uploaded my final .blend file for anyone to edit themselves.
I included the fullsize Face Hugger Egg I meshed/edited.
I also include the fullsize Face Hugger Egg with the tendrils cut off and then separate files for the tendrils. I named them NE, NW, SE, SW for the directions I saw them in as I cut them out.
As you place the tendrils you'll notice they have a specific orientation relative to Cardinal coordinates. This is how they'll be attached to the base egg. Use whatever methods you feel works to attach them.

How to Make it:
Using a LULZBot TAZ 5, one tendril takes up almost the whole bed. The egg itself without the tendrils does too.... SO that's why I cut it up into the 5 pieces. Have fun and well.... patience is a virtue but not so hard to achieve when something cool is in store for the future :)

If you use this thingi for your Face Hugger, then print with the lightest infill and shell that your printer will let you get away with. I don't like PLA but it sure has it's uses. If you print this whole thing in a translucent PLA, even natural PLA, you can light the inside so if you can make a nice enough paint job while keeping as much transluscency as possible, you'll have a damn near real Face Hugger Egg :D

How to assemble it:
I recommend drilling one or more large holes in each connection point. From there you can add some epoxy, glue, caulk, or other adhesive that takes up a large volume, and creates a solid bond.
A plastic welder will do wonders for post seam adhesion and cleaning up any gaps. A plastic welder will do well in your 3D printer arsenal if you don't have one yet ;)

SO now I should have some wicked props for the house when people walk in my front door :)

Notes:

To use 0% infill you must use the 0% infill egg. Otherwise you will need some infill. I recommend natural or translucent green PLA for this one since it is translucent and will have that neat transparent effect.
If you use 1mm walls and the 0% infill, the supports can break your model when you clean it up. Give your supports the greatest reasonable distance for your initial settings and all should be well. Otherwise, just be careful.
I do not recommend removing the support material from the bottom inside of the model. It creates a good solid stand, no one will ever see it, so why not?

Once it's cleaned up, a heat gun or hair dryer will help curl all the support nonsense that's left and since this is a creepy model, the ugly curling will actually work to you benefit.

To secure the tendrils to the egg, I recommend drilling holes in each side of the flat spots (egg and tendril sides) and use an epoxy to glue them. You can use ABS/Acetone glue here too and it will have a great bond but having something leak into the drill holes on either side will create a bridge/plug that will be almost impossible to remove without breaking something which would be the goal.

ABS could be used and with ABS/acetone glue you could paint it down. If you use a neon green ABS, it dries near clear with a green tint that builds up as the layer is thicker. It also is just as smooth as an acetone vapor bath with ABS. In fact, you can use ABS/Acetone glue to paint on ABS and still give it the same vapor bath effect, just less deadly....

After the ABS/acetone post process or a nice paint job, a final coat of liquid latex should be a nice finish.

comments.text: This is not a good idea. The holes where the z axis threaded rods go through are over sized for a reason. A rod that is not perfectly straight, as many are not, needs to be free to wobble otherwise the bearing on the smooth rod will bind as the threaded rod will apply undesirable force to the bearing. A bit of threaded rod wobble does not matter as it is the smooth rods and bearings that stabilise the Z axis.

comments.author: Geoffs

comments.text: The hole in the top bracket is larger than the threaded rod diameter for a good reason, this is a deliberate design decision. Many threaded rods are not perfectly straight. The top end of the rod is left free to wobble so any small bend in the rod has no effect on the X or Z axis accuracy. Putting a cap on a bent rod will stop the wobble at the top, but the rod is still bent. This causes the wobble to show up further down the rod so the motor and smooth rod bearing will struggle to try and straighten the threaded rod.a slightly bent rod is not an issue if the top end is leftfree to move,  however a badly bent rod  (ie the wobble at the top is too great to be accommodated by the hole in the top bracket) should be replaced. Putting caps on perfectly straight rods is probably ok but why bother? But capping a slightly bent rod defeats the deliberate design decision and will cause problems with increased friction, binding and stress on the coupler.

description.text:
My Tronxy X1 is an amazing printer but it does have its problems. One of those problems was the original fanmount. It was placed a little to low, which gave the poor printer a hard time getting up to temperature.
To combat this problem, I printed the body of the supercooler (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1906391).

Although this was a good solution to the getting-up-to-temperature problem, this caused another problem: extreme stringing.

The low placed cooler had as benefit that it would cool the extruded plastic as well.
New goal: I had to find an elegant and light way to add a 50mm radial fan I ordered to cool the extruded plastic.

On thingiverse I found this post: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2184575.
It had two benefits:

  1. It was a design for a extruder mount resembling mine.
  2. It was a mount for only a radial fan with minimal weight and a nice form factor.

After printing it and combining it with the 360 nozzle fan (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1620630.) I found the fanduct to be place to high and cool the hotend to much, which resulted in the original problem reocurring.

Since I really liked the design and sturdyness of the mount, I decided to remodel it and change it to be able to mount it to the left side of my mount without hitting the limit sensor.

EDIT: The solidworks part is not very organised since I made this very shortly after starting working with 3d design software. If you just want to use it in an assembly, I suggest only adding the step file.

TL;DR: I wanted to add a part cooler to my Tronxy X1 but could not find a print online that fitted my needs. So I moddeled one.

title: Y Carriage Belt Mount/Tensioner for Folger Tech 2020 i3

description.text:
This is a Y carriage belt mount with integrated tensioner for the FolgerTech 2020 i3. It allows the belt to be centered on the bed rather than offset as is the one that comes with the kit. I also wanted to integrate some sort of tensioner and didn't like many of the ones I found that placed the tensioner on the front frame of the printer. For something that rarely needs adjusted I wanted something a bit more subtle and out of the way.

I designed this to use knurled brass inserts (1x M5x7mm, 8x M3x5mm) but plan on creating a version that can use regular nuts when I get a chance and will add it here when I do. I extended the holes past the inserts so that a variety of screw lengths could work and tapered them down so that they would grip the screw like a lock-nut. The inserts were just heat set with a soldering iron.

The tensioner uses an M5 bolt and a length of 20-30mm should work depending on how much travel you want. I'm currently using an M5-0.8 30mm socket cap bolt. You may need to post-process the tensioner block hole so that the screw can more easily rotate within it. I just ran the screw in and out a few times with a drill to loosen it up a bit. The block should rest against the mounting plate enough to keep it from rotating as you tighten/loosen the tensioner screw.

The ridges on the belt mounts fit the GT2 profile well enough to grip it without the need for significant pressure so that stress is limited on the belt and plastic.

Yep, yet another filament guide design for the Anet A8. This one fits behind the top support and replaces two of the 7mm spacers used to hold the LCD in place. This was designed for the Anet A8, so I do not know if it will work for similar printers (like the TronXY p802) or other Anet options (like the A6).

There are two options available - one with a solid loop, and one that has a slot for feeding the filament through. This slot was sized for 1.75mm filament, but I don't know if 3mm can be squeezed through.

7/21/2017 update: I've made a version of this filament guide that fits the Anet A6. You can find this version here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2446606

3/3/2018 update: Apparently sometime recently the Anet A8's frame went through a minor redesign, so I have added a V2 of these filament guides that should fit the new frame. One way to tell if your A8 frame needs the version 1 or version 2 guide is to measure from the center of the top mounting hole to the left edge of the display frame (or right edge if you're printing this mirrored). If this measurement is 10mm, then you should print up the original version. If this is 12mm, then go with version 2 instead.

description.text:
Ancient poems warn of a narrow channel of water so treacherous that death touches all who approach. Sailors must choose to risk their ship, traveling close to the monstrous whirlpool Charybdis, or instead hug the rocky shoals where dwells a creature some say is made from the nightmares of all men.

Scylla, they call her, Horror of the Sea. No ship that dares sail in her waters goes unscathed. Those that cling to survival whisper panicked tales of enormous black tentacles tipped with slavering hound heads ravaging whole ships to splinters with pitiless precision. Though it’s her laughter, they say, that’s most horrible; child-like, delighting in blood soaked murder as men are dragged into the dark abyss.

Poets have tried to romanticize this beast, to provide some humanity to her monstrosity. They write she was once a beautiful Naiad, wronged by a jealous priestess and transformed. Yet the old poems say she was born this way, beget by gods full of jealousy and loathing; dropped into the sea to terrorize mankind.

Would that she had remained in the sea, but the nightmare has come ashore. Dragged by dog-headed tentacles she roams our streets, plucks us from our beds, and fills the night with disturbing laughter. Scylla has come, and not even the gods can help us.

description.text:
A small planetary gears system with a ratio of 4:1 per stage, as many stages as wanted, small, open enclosure to see the gears, and hardware free. The gears are designed with a circular pitch of 2.5mm and they are also slightly beveled at the tips of the teeth to avoid the need of cleaning the excess of material from the firsts layers. The OpenSCAD is not parametric, there's only parameters for clearance (set to 0.2), backslash (set to 0.1), pressure angle (set to 22.5), tolerances between nuts and bolts (set to 0.4) and length of the bolts, sometimes referred as rods. Any other change will not work. To play with the OpenSCAD you will need the following libraries: Public Domain Involute Parameterized Gears by LeemonBaird
thingiverse.com/thing:5505 Poor man's openscad screw library
thingiverse.com/thing:8796 Knurled surface finishing library
thingiverse.com/thing:9095 The libraries have been included in the ZIP file together with STL files for every single part, build plates for complete sets from 1 to 4 stages, just the crank and upgrade kits from 1 stage to 2, 3 or 4. 1 minute video: http://youtu.be/MUH0MGP7AGc A shorter video (59") featuring a 10 stages set: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FyVZ31tLGCU&feature=plcp More Pics: http://www.flickr.com/photos/aubenc/sets/72157629731990190/

My setup is a Makerbot Replicator with 0.4mm nozzle, ReplicatorG - 0034 and Skeinforge 47. The gears where not printing fine with the standard profile and printomatic, also, the threads like to print slowly and a little bit fat. It is important to set Layer Height at 0.25mm (or the planets can find it hard to spin). Infill should not be set bellow 60% or the bolts will break too easyly! (The profile I used is included in the ZIP file) Use multiply to print 4 planets and see if you need to adjust the profile. Then print the stage to be sure that the gears are usable. If you don't clean the sides of the teeth it will be a tight fit perfectly usable. If you clean them they may be too loose. Be very careful with the bolts, do not fasten the nuts too much (just a very little bit) and be extremely careful when using the crank Update: Scaling this thing I'm always afraid about the result of scaling multipart things, specially when the design is full of threads and gears. Check out the awesome set printed by mread ( thingiverse.com/derivative:29726 ) He scaled it up by 25% and it looks terrific! I don't know what are the specs of the printer he used but it could very well well be the case that scaling this thing up by 25% is the right thing to do when the extruder is equiped with a 0.5mm nozzle. Let's check it out! bot1334 has a 0.6mm nozzle so I scaled it up by 50% (0.6 / 0.4), sliced at 0.4mm layer height and... I had a lot of trouble with the threads taped in the plates. Amazingly, the issues disappeared when I lowered down the layer height to 0.38mm. Is it a coincidence that 0.38 is close to 0.25 scaled up a 50%? description.text:
This is a 7th grade astronomy project in which groups of 2 students create a 3D model of what the first permanent base on Mars might look like. Students worked in pairs using the Share function on Tinkercad to collaborate on the design. This was the first time I used the Share function with a class and I'm happy to report it worked perfectly!

Student created models are included here, along with a sample of the lab report.

This is the second year doing this project with students. The original project was a bit different and can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:873532

Print models with brim and support.
NGSS

This was part of a 7th grade astronomy unit about the solar system. After learning about the inner planets students were asked to think about what a permanent base on Mars would look like. Students did some research to see examples of what experts like NASA and Space-X imagine a base on Mars would look like. 
Students worked in pairs to design their vision of what a permanent base on Mars would look like. The model was created using Tinkercad and the Share option to allow students to edit the file at the same time. Completed models were marked with letters to identify the structures. A screen shot of the model was included in the lab report, along with a description of each structure.
Because students were turning in a screenshot of their base they could make it detailed and elaborate without worrying about whether it could be printed.  Their models were printed, those that were printable, using brim and support.
Students set up their Mars base models and shared with their fellow students.

• Pairs of students research what a permanent base on Mars would look like.
  • Each pair of students builds a model of their vision of a permanent base on Mars using Tinkercad and the Share function to edit the file together.
  • Students used letters to identify each structure or vehicle included in their base.
  • A screenshot of their base in added to their lab report and they create a key describing each structure in their base.
  • As many models as possible from each group's project were printed (use brim and support).
  • Each group put the pieces together to create their model on the tabletop.
  • Students circulated around the room to view each other's work.
Just some plastic and a 3D printer.

title: Wall hanger for larger external hard drive enclosures

description.text:
Needed to hang an WD external drive on a wall, so this was the result. It is flanged on one side so that it will keep the drive from sliding out of the mount. You need to mirror print one to handle the opposite end. The added holes and flat surface insets are to add a bit of strength and (just maybe) some 'class' to the design. ;-) The print ends up being more than strong enough for the drive. ...So much so that I will probably make something similar to hang laptops on a wall.

Sorry, don't have a picture of it in use within it's native habitat.

Hope someone finds it useful.
Bill
